r child at another school that has an opening.What do I need to know before registering my child?You should be aware that your child does not have a guaranteed place at a school until you have registered the child at that school.The principal of the school must give you the admissions policy of the school and explain it to you.You should also ask which language/s are used for teaching at the school and decide if that is suitable for your child.You should also find out what school fees the school charges.If you cannot afford the fees, you should ask the principal or school official about how you can apply for full or partial exemption from paying the fees.A public school may not administer any test for admission to a school.A test may only be used for deciding which courses or programmes your child should do at the school.You should ask to see the school's code of conduct and make sure that you are willing to sign it.Which documents are required when making an application?* Birth certificate or identity document of the child; and* Immunisation card for the child; and* Transfer card or last school report card for learners who have been to school previously.(Note that baptismal certificates will not be regarded as proof of birth date.)What other documents are required if I am not a South African citizen?* Study permit; and* Temporary or permanent residence permit form the Department of Home Affairs; or* Evidence that you have applied for permission to stay in South AfricaHow do I know if my child has been accepted at the school?The Provincial Department of Education, through the school principal, must inform you of the outcome of your application.What can I do if my child is refused admission to a school?You can request a written explanation from the department, through the school principal.If you are not satisfied with the reasons given for the decision, you may lodge a written appeal to the MEC for education in the province.CONTENTS: Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy GuideHome > Publications > Public Information > A > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt School FeesSchool FeesThe school will ask you to pay school fees.The amount is set a at a public meeting of the School Governing Body (SGB), which must be held each year an where parents vote on the amount of school fees to be paid.However, if you cannot afford the required amount or can pay a lesser amount, you may write a letter to the SGB requesting full or part exemption from paying school fees.The SGB will inform you of its decision.A copy of the regulations dealing with school fees can be obtained from the school.The school must assist you if you need help with your application for exemption.* How do I appeal against the decision of the SGB?* If exempted from paying school fees, can my child be refused access to the school?* If exempted from paying school fees, can my child be refused access to any school activities or have his/her results withheld?* Can I get financial assistance to pay school fees?* How do I apply for grants to which I am entitled?How do I appeal against the decision of the SGB?You can lodge an appeal with the Provincial Head of the Education Department.She/he will explain the reasons in writing if you were not granted exemption.If it is determined that you can afford to pay the fees, and fail to do so, legal steps can be taken against you to ensure that you pay any outstanding fees.If exempted from paying school fees, can my child be refused access to the school?If exempted from paying school fees, can my child be refused access to any school activities or have his/her results withheld?No. The school cannot withhold your child's results or exclude him/her any educational activity if you cannot afford to pay school fees.Can I get financial assistance to pay school fees?You can get partial or complete exemption from paying school fees based on your income.You can increase your income by claiming grants that you may qualify for.Two grants you might qualify for are:* The Child Support Grant: This is given to a primary caregiver that cares for a child/children who are under the age of seven.The caregiver can be the mother, father, grandparent, relative, friend or older brother/sister.* The Foster Child Grant: This is for children who are placed with a person who is not the parnet, such as a grandparent.A court must endorse the foster relationship.How do I apply for grants to which I am entitled?You should apply at the Welfare Office or your nearest Magistrate's Office.The officials will ask you questions and fill in a form using your answers.Home > Publications > Public Information > A > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt GovernanceGovernance* What is a school governing body (SGB)?* How do I get elected to represent other parents on the governing body?* How do I get to know about the election process?* What happens if I'm not elected onto the school governing body?* Who makes the decision about school matters?* Where can I lodge an objection against a decision or action?What is a school governing body (SGB)?An SGB is a structure that governs the school.It stands in a position of trust towards the school.It is made up of the principal, elected representatives of educators, non-educator staff, parents and learners, in the case of secondary schools.The SGB can also select persons in the community who have special skills to be non-voting members of the SGB.How do I get elected to represent other parents on the governing body?You can represent other parents on a governing body if you are nominated and voted for by parents.The SGB is elected for a three-year period.You can stand at the next election.As soon as your last child leaves the school, you must resign your seat, as you no longer have any rights on the SGB.Parents can be re-elected as long as they have children in the school.How do I get to know about the election process?The principal/SGB of the school is required by law to provide all parents with information about the election of parents onto the governing body.You should vote in each SGB election.What happens if I'm not elected onto the school governing body?Even if you are not elected onto the school governing body, you should support the school's SGB in its work and you must respond to written notices calling for a response.You have the RIGHT to be involved in the affairs of the school through attending meetings of parents or other meetings organised by the school, including the SGB's Annual General Meeting.The school must give you at least 30 days notice before this meeting is to be held.At this meeting the SGB must present its budget and annual financial report.The school must present a report concerning its activities at least once a year.You also have the RIGHT to be consulted by the educators or the principal about the schooling activities of our child.The principal and the educators at the school must notify you in good time and regularly about the well-being, behaviour, attendance and learning progress of you child.You must also be informed and represent your child at any disciplinary proceedings against your child in terms of the school's Code of Conduct.Who makes the decision about school matters?The Head of the Provincial Education Department, through the principal, takes all decisions about education in the school.You should be informed about these decisions and have the right to information concerning the school and your child's education.Your school must also have a Code of Conduct.You have the right to be consulted regarding the preparation and amendment of the Code of Conduct.Where can I lodge an objection against a decision or action?You can lodge an objection against a decision or action of:* an educator, with the principal;* a principal, with the Head of the Education Department in the province;* a representative council of learners member, with the school governing body; and,* a school governing body member, with the MEC or Head of Department.Home > Publications > Public Information > A > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt Language of Learning and TeachingLanguage of Learning and Teaching* What does the Language-in-Education Policy say?* Will my child not be disadvantaged by being taught in a language other than English?* Who decides on the language of learning and teaching?* Does my child have options regarding the language of learning and teaching in a school?What does the Language-in-Education Policy say?The Department's Language-in-Education Policy encourages learners to learn more that one language.It also encourages them to use the language that they best understand as the language of learning and teaching.They can learn other languages as subjects or add other languages as languages of instruction.Will my child not be disadvantaged by being taught in a language other than English?Learning through the home language during the first years of formal schooling ensures a solid foundation for future learning, as well as the acquisition of new/other languages.Who decides on the language of learning and teaching?The SGB must decide on the language of learning and teaching used in a school.The language used will depend on the preference of the majority of learners in the school and the ability of the school to teach in the preferred language.In addition, the SGB needs to indicate how it will promote multilingualism in the school.Does my child have options regarding the language of learning and teaching in a school?Each learner must, upon registration at a school, indicate the preferred language of learning and teaching.Any of our 11 languages may be indicated as the language of learning and teaching in a public school.Where there are more than 30 children requesting a particular language, the school must make an effort to offer tuition in that language.Home > Publications > Public Information > A > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt You Have the Following Responsibilities as a ParentYou Have the Following Responsibilities as a Parent* How should I contribute towards the development of my child's school?* What role can I play in supporting the learning process of my child?* How can I keep abreast of the developments at the school?How should I contribute towards the development of my child's school?As a parent, you have a responsibility to contribute towards the development of the school by rendering services to the school.This may include making yourself available to participate in the activities of the school such as the maintenance of school property, auditing of financial statements, managing sports events, helping manage school trips etc.What role can I play in supporting the learning process of my child?Your child is in the custody of the school staff when she/he is at the school.The school staff can successfully carryout their teaching responsibilities if they receive the support of the parents.As a parent you have the responsibility to:* make sure that your child attends school regularly;* assist with the discipline of your child;* assist the school in promoting a culture of mutual respect and tolerance;* monitor your child's educational progress;* ensure that she/he completes her/his homework;* liase with the school staff; and* respond to school notices calling for responses.How can I keep abreast of developments at the school?Parents of learners must take responsibility for attending school meetings that are organised for them.The SGB is legally bound to report to the parents of learners at the school form time to time, and should keep parents informed about issues that affect them.You have the right to request any additional information that is of interest to you from the SGB and the principal of the school.The SGB or principal must supply this information, or tell you in writing why they cannot give the information.Home > Publications > Public Information > A > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt Contact InformationContact InformationFor further information please contact any of the following provincial Departments of Education at these numbers:ProvinceTelephone numberFax number021 467 2768021 467 2996011 355 0552011 355 0206035 874 8411/3592053 839 6701053 838 6640018 384 2828018 384 3432040 642 3284040 643 3198Mpumalanga013 766 5317013 766 5577051 404 8424051 404 8160Limpopo015 290 7908015 297 3154Published by the Education Human Resources Development, Gender Equity and School Safety Chief Directorate and the Directorate: National and Provincial Communication, Department of Education, Sol Plaatje House, 123 Schoeman Street, PretoriaHome > Publications > Public Information > A > All you Need to Know about the Registration of Non-Profit Organisations &gt All You Need to Know about the Registration of a Non-Profit Organisation (NPO)All You Need to Know about the Registration of a Non-Profit Organisation (NPO)The Nonprofit Organisations Act 71 of 1997The NPO Directorate within the Department of Social Development registers organisations under the Nonprofit Organisations Act No.71 of 1997.The Primary Purpose of this Act is to encourage and support organisations in a wide range of work they do by:* creating an enabling environment for NPOs to flourished.* setting and maintaining adequate standards of governance, accountability and transparency.The Act provides a voluntary registration facility for NPOs.WHAT IS AN NPO?A Nonprofit Organisation is defined as: a trust, company or other association of persons:- (a) established for a public purpose, and (b) the income and property of which are not distributable to its members or office bearers except as reasonable compensation for services rendered.WHICH ORGANISATIONS CAN APPLY FOR NPO STATUS?Any organisation that is not for profit and is not part of government can apply for registration.; that is:* Non- Governmental Organisations (NGO)* Community Based Organisations (CBO)* Faith Based Organisations (FBO)* Organisations that have registered as Section 21 Companies under the Company Act 61 of 1973.* Trusts that have registered with Master of the Supreme Court under the Trust Property Control Act 57 of 1988.* Any other Voluntary Association that is not-for-profit.The Directorate can only register an organisation that has a constitution or any other founding document.HOW LONG DOES THE REGISTRATION PROCESS TAKE?It would take about two months to process the entire registration.HOW MUCH DOES IT COST?To register a Nonprofit Organisation is free of charge.HOW DO ORGANISATIONS REGISTER?By submitting to the NPO Directorate:* A Complete Application Form (obtainable from the Dept); and* Two copies of the organisation's founding document i.e. a constitution or a deed of Trust or Memorandum and Articles of Association.WHAT ARE THE BENEFITS FOR REGISTRATIONThere are many benefits to be gained from a system of registering nonprofit organisations.* Improve the credibility of the sector because NPOs can account to a public office.* Brings organisations into a formal system.* Help the sector to get organized.* Help in finding ways of getting benefits like tax incentives and funding opportunitiesCONTENTS: All you Need to Know about the Registration of Non-Profit OrganisationsHome > Publications > Public Information > A > All you Need to Know about the Registration of Non-Profit Organisations &gt NPO's Frequently Asked QuestionNPO's Frequently Asked Question1. How do organisations apply?Fill-in the registrations form together with two copies of organisation founding documents or constitutions to the NPO Directorate2. Which organisations can apply?Any organisation that is not for profit and is not part of government can apply for registration i.e. Voluntary Association/NGO's, Section 21 Companies, and Trusts.3. How much does it cost to register an NPO?NPO registration is free of charge.4. Where do I find an application form and model constitution?An application form is available on request from Department, Telephone numbers (012) 312-7500 or on this web site.Send the documents to Departments of Social Development, Private Bag x901, Pretoria, 0001 or Human Science Research Council (HSRC) Building, Fifth Floor South 134 Pretorius Street, Pretoria, 0001.5. What are the benefits for registration6. Is the government funding NPO's after registration?The NPO Directorate's role is to register organisations and not to fund them.The Act only creates an enabling enviroment for organisations to operate and flourish.7. What is an Accounting Officer?In terms of Close Corporation Act of 1984 an Accounting Officer is a registered person paid to deal with organisations books of accounts according to accounting and financial procedures and principles.8. How can we appeal against the decision of directorate after de-registration?Send us a letter of appeal and you will be informed about the exact date of hearing.9. Can I re-apply after being de-registered?Yes you can re-apply by sending us the original certificates and two copies of the organisation founding documents as well as the application form.Home > Publications > Public Information > A > All you Need to Know about the Registration of Non-Profit Organisations &gt NPO DocumentsNPO Documents* NPO Model Constitution* NPO Questions* NPO Application Form* NPO Narrative Report* Codes of Good Practice for OrganisationsHome > Publications > Public Information > A > All you Need to Know about the Registration of Non-Profit Organisations &gt Steps in the Registration ProcessSteps in the Registration Process1. Complete an application form together with two c