Hooper, who promised them their freedom.They concentrated on the slaves of Pieter Louw of the Swartland and spread the uprising towards Koeberg and Tygervalley.In total 34 farms were plundered, the farmers bound and taken prisoner.When the slaves began to march to Cape Town, the Govenor, the Earl of Caledon, dispatched soldiers to the troubled area and all 326 slaves were taken prisoner.Five of the ringleaders were hanged publicly and their corpses were displayed in order to deter anyone of like mind.Large numbers of slaves worked in the labour-intensive wheat farms and mixed farming areas found in the Swartland and West Coast.Many mission stations in this area also testify to the missionary work done among the Khoekhoen and the slaves.The well-known ones are Wupperthal and Mamre, but there is also Papendorp, Troe-Troe Mission station in Van Rhynsdorp and Ebenhaezer.Places of slave remembrance in the West CoastMamreGoedverwachtWupperthalClick here for a map of the West Coast.Mamre (historic village and mission station on the R307) A mission station was established at Groene-kloof (Mamre) near Malmesbury in 1808 by the Moravian Missionary Society at a former military outpost on the farm Louwplaas as well as the farms De Groene Kloof and Cruywagenskraal.The missionaries Kohrhammer and Schmidt set out to work among the local Khoekhoen but the mission station also served as a haven for freed slaves.Today the old kerkwerf (churchyard) can still be seen as well as a mill, bakery, stables and a school.Tel: 021 576 1134Moravian church in MamreGoedverwacht, Burgershoek near Piketberg (off the R399 between Piketberg and Velddrif) This settlement was the lawful property of a group of former slaves, who inherited the farm Burgerskloof from the owner, Hendrik Schalk Burger, upon emancipation in 1838.He left the farm to his slave Maniesa and her five children on condition that they take care of him until his death.His own children later contested the will, but the court upheld it and the farm remained Maniesa's property up to the death of her last child Hester in 1888.Her grave can be seen in the graveyard.Goedverwacht, a Moravian mission station, was established here later when the slave descendants sold the land to the Moravian missionaries for ¬£750.Tel: 022 912 4784 or 022 912 4207Wupperthal (R364, 74 km from Clanwilliam) In 1828 two Rhenish missionaries, Johann Gottlieb Leipoldt and J von Wurm jointly bought the farm Rietmond on the Tratra River in the Cedarberg District.A mission station was established and named Wupperthal after the missionaries' home town in Germany.A large number of freed slaves settled here after emancipation.The Rhenish Missionary Society started several industries, namely, masonry, millinery, leather tanning, woodwork, thatching and shoe-making, an industry that is still practised.Today it is a Moravian mission station.Tel: 027 492 3004 Church officeLong house, MamreGoedverwacht mission stationHome > Publications > Public Information > R > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt Admission of Your Child to a SchoolHome > Publications > Public Information > R &gt Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy GuideHome > Publications > Public Information > R > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt School FeesHome > Publications > Public Information > R > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt GovernanceHome > Publications > Public Information > R > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt Language of Learning and TeachingHome > Publications > Public Information > R > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt You Have the Following Responsibilities as a ParentHome > Publications > Public Information > R > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt Contact InformationHome > Publications > Public Information > S &gt Sexually Transmitted Infection (STI)Home > Publications > Public Information > S &gt Cervical Cancer Fact Sheet for Health WorkersHome > Publications > Public Information > S > Student Guide to Funding - NSFAS &gt IntroductionStudents who need to fund their own studies have limited options, such as private loans from banks, part-time employment, assistance from family members and, for the lucky few, bursaries.For those who are academically deserving and financially needy, there is another option: NSFAS (National Student Financial Aid Scheme) offers a unique opportunity to access a loan, part of which can be converted to a bursary.The scheme also runs a number of loan or bursary schemes on behalf of other organisations and bodies, such as the Department of Labour.Get more information about these options from the Financial Aid Bureau at the university or technikon where you intend studying or where you have registered.What is NSFAS?The National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) is a loan and bursary scheme operating in terms of Act 56 of 1999 and funded by the National Department of Education.Where does TEFSA fit it?TEFSA, established in 1991, managed and administered the National Student Financial Aid Scheme since its inception in 1996.Act 56 of 1999 converted TEFSA into a statutory body called NSFAS in July 2000.CONTENTS: Student Guide to Funding - NSFASHome > Publications > Public Information > S > Student Guide to Funding - NSFAS &gt How, What, When, Where ...How, What, When, Where ...What does NSFAS Offer?* The means to obtain a tertiary education.* Loans at low interest rates.* Loans without guarantees.* A reasonable repayment plan.What is a Loan?* A loan is money you borrow to cover tertiary studies.* This Loan has to be repaid.What is a Bursary?* A bursary is that portion of the award that does not need to be repaid.* The size of the bursary is dependent on your academic success.Who Qualifies for a NSFAS Loan?To qualify for a loan you must be:* registered at a South African university or technikon* an undergraduate, studying for a first tertiary educational qualification, or* studying for a second tertiary qualification, if this is necessary to practise in your chosen profession (eg LLB or HDE)* able to demonstrate potential for academic success* financially needy.How Much Money do you Get?The maximum award in 2004 was R25,000 and the minimum was R2,000.What is the Role of the University an Technikon's Financial Aid Bureaux?* Offer advice about loans.* Assist with loan applications.* Explain how you access the money and how you have to repay the money.* Evaluate your ability to succeed in your chosen course.* Conduct a means test that will determine whether you are really among the financially needy.Where do you Apply for a Loan?From Financial Aid Bureaux at the university or technikon where you are/or plan on studying.How is the Bursary Component of your Loan Calculated?Up to 40% of the award may be converted into a bursary, dependent on your end of year results.* If you pass all the courses for which you have registered, you qualify for a 40% bursary.* If you pass three quarters of the courses, you qualify for a 30% bursary.* If you pass half of the courses, you qualify for a 20% bursary.* If you pass one quarter of the courses, you qualify for a 10% bursary.* If you pass none of the courses, you qualify for no bursary at all.What Happens if You Have Money Left Over in Your Account?* You can't receive more money from NSFAS than you require.* If there is money left over in your fee account at the end of the year (for example, if you received a bursary or a merit award after the NSFAS award was granted), the Financial Aid Bureau has to return the money to NSFAS.This will count as your first loan repayment.* Money left over in your account is never paid out to you.Furthermore, it is in your interest to ensure that the money is returned to NSFAS to avoid paying interest on it.What about Interest?Interest on NSFAS awards will be calculated at 7% for 2004 as of 1 April 2004.What Is Interest and Why does NSFAS Charge It?Interest is the cost of borrowing money.Money, like any other commodity, has a price attached to it.If you deposit money into a bank account, you earn interest - in other words, the bank pays you because it can make use of your money while it is deposited with them.When you take back your money, you stop earning interest.If you borrow money from the bank, you have to pay the bank for the use of their money.In previous years commercial banks have charged as much as 23% interest on student loans.If you had received one of these loans you would be required to pay back the loan within a specific period whether you are employed or not.By comparison, NSFAS's interest rate is equal to the rate of inflation (typically in the late 1990s 9%) plus 2%.This 2% helps sustain the loan scheme.It contributes towards the administration costs and the shortfall resulting from death and long-term non-repayment due to unemployment.What is Inflation?* Each year money loses value and can buy less.* The decline in the value of money from one year to the next is called inflation.* An example of how inflation affects your studies is the increase in fees each year.* In order for NSFAS to be able to assist students in future, NSFAS has to try to make sure that the value of its money is retained.That is why its interest rate is tied to the inflation rate.* NSFAS's interest rate is low because it is subsidised by donations from government, private sector companies and overseas donors.Home > Publications > Public Information > S > Student Guide to Funding - NSFAS &gt Paying Back the LoanPaying Back the LoanWhen Do You Start to Pay Back?Once you are employed and your annual salary is R26,300 or more.How Much Do You Pay Back?* The repayments are worked out at a rate that will not place a great burden on you.* Therefore, repayments are based on the salary that you earn.* And repayments only start once your salary is R26,300 or more per year (ie R2,192 per month).At this level your repayment is 3% of your annual salary.The rate at which you repay your loan is reflected in the Ready Reckoner Table.How Do You Pay Back?* NSFAS sends quarterly statements to all students and will later send a letter information you of your settlement terms once you become eligible to pay back your loan.This happens once you start earning over R26 300 a year.* You are then expected to make the necessary arrangements.These can include a debit order on your bank account, direct deposits into the NSFAS account, postal orders, cheques or employer deductions.* While NSFAS will inform you how much you need to pay, it is your responsibility to ensure that you keep in touch withHome > Publications > Public Information > S > Student Guide to Funding - NSFAS &gt 10 Things You Need to Know about NSFAS10 Things You Need to Know about NSFAS1. NSFAS was established by the South African Government in 1996.2. It was set up to ensure that students, who have potential but cannot afford to fund their own studies, will have access to funding for tertiary education.3. It is funded by the government, international donors and the private sector.4. TEFSA, which was established in 1991, managed and administered the scheme until 2000 when TEFSA became NSFAS.5. All of the financial assistance received by a successful applicant takes the form of a loan.6. Up to 40% of loans can be converted into bursaries, depending on students' pass rates.7. Loan repayments are recycled to help future generations of students.8. The NSFAS Act of 1999 allows NSFAS to have employers deduct loan repayments from monthly salaries of those who have received assistance from the Scheme.9. Loan repayments are based on individuals' earnings.10. The interest charged on loans is subsidised and therefore considerably less than the commercial rate which is charged by banks.Home > Publications > Public Information > S > Student Guide to Funding - NSFAS &gt Further InformationFurther InformationFor further details, please approach the Financial Aid Bureau at the university or technikon where you intend studying or at which you are registered.You can also visit the NSFAS website at www.nsfas.org.za.Home > Publications > Public Information > S &gt Student Guide to Funding - NSFASHome > Publications > Public Information > T &gt Tips for TenderingHome > Publications > Public Information > T > Government Financial Assistance &gt Grants, Benefits And Compensation: An OverviewGrants, Benefits And Compensation: An OverviewThere are a number of forms of financial relief available to different people in different circumstances, including:* The Unemployment Insurance Fund* The Occupational Injuries and Diseases Compensation Fund* The Road Accidents FundWho can claim from which fund?GrantsThere are a number of grants for poor people provided by the South African Social Security Agency.All grants are for poor people only (a "means test" applies).Unemployment InsuranceIf you have been employed, you can get unemployment insurance benefits from the Unemployment Insurance Fund (UIF) run by the National Department of Labour.CompensationIf you are temporarily or permanently disabled because of an accident at work, you can get compensation from the Compensation Fund at the National Department of Labour.If you are injured in a motor vehicle accident, you can get compensation from the Road Accident Fund for your medical expenses, disablement, and loss of income.Home > Publications > Public Information > T > Government Financial Assistance &gt Social Security GrantsSocial Security GrantsThe South African Social Security Agency (SASSA) has three types of grant for looking after children:* Child Support Grant* Care Dependency Grant* Foster Child Grant.You can get a child support grant for each child under 14, if you are the child's primary care-giver.You can get a care dependency grant for each child under 18 who needs full-time care because of a physical or mental disability, if you are the child's parent or guardian.Both of these grants depend on how poor you are.You can get a foster child grant if you have been legally appointed a foster parent by a court.Whether you get this grant depends on how poor the child is, NOT on how poor you are.However, you CAN get a foster child grant and a care dependency grant, if you qualify for both.For adults, SASSA has the following kinds of grants:* Old age grant* Disability grant* War veteran's grant.The old age grant is for women over 60 and men over 65.The disability grant is for adults over 18 who are not able to work because of their disability.If you were disabled because of an accident at work, you may be able to get compensation from the Occupational Injuries Compensation Fund .If you were disabled because of a motor vehicle accident, you may be able to get compensation from the Road Accident Fund.The war veterans grant is for adults over 60 or anyone who is unable to work because of a disability, and who served in the 1st or 2nd World War or the Korean War.The provincial Department of Social Development can also provide temporary help in crisis situations with a financial award called "social relief of distress".This is for people who cannot provide for their families' basic needs because of a crisis of a temporary nature.Home > Publications > Public Information > T > Government Financial Assistance &gt Unemployment Insurance Fund (UIF) BenefitsUnemployment Insurance Fund (UIF) BenefitsIf you have been employed before, then you can collect Unemployment Insurance from the Unemployment Insurance Fund (UIF) if you have been unemployed for more than 14 days.If you have never had a job you cannot claim from the UIF.Everyone who works for more than 24 hours per month is supposed to be registered with the UIF and to make a contribution of 1% of their earnings (along with contributions from their employer) to the UIF.If you have been contributing, you can claim benefits if you become unemployed (if you are fired or retrenched, but not if you quit).You must claim your UIF benefit within 6 months of becoming unemployed.How much you can claim and for how long you can claim depend on how long you were working and how much you were earning.You can get one day's benefit for every 6 days you worked, up to a maximum of 238 days (which you reach after working for 4 years).You cannot claim any benefit for any amount of time that you worked and at the same time received a Social Services grant for yourself.If you earned more than R8099 per month before, you will get a flat benefit of R101,18 per day.For example, if you earned R1000 per month before, you will get R17,34 per day.UIF can also be claimed by the partner or dependants of a worker who has died.You can also get a UIF benefit if you can't work because of ill-health (for up to 6 months, but takes into account any sick leave).You can get a maternity benefit when you have a child, or an adoption benefit if you adopt a child younger than two years and have to take off work to look after the child.Only one parent can get maternity or adoption benefits.You must apply for the maternity benefit at least eight weeks before the birth of the child.You must apply for the adoption benefit within 6 months of the adoption order.You can apply for UIF benefits at any Labour CentreHome > Publications > Public Information > T > Government Financial Assistance &gt Occupational Injuries Compensation Fund (formerly Workers' Compensation)Occupational Injuries Compensation Fund (formerly Workers' Compensation)The accident must be identified by its date, time and place and must have happened as a direct result of your employment.For temporary total disablement, you can get compensation equal to 75% of your monthly earnings, up to a maximum of R2 868,00 per week.For permanent disablement, where the degree of disablement is 30% or less, you can get a lump sum (one payment) which is usually equal to 15 times your monthly earnings.However, the minimum lump sum is 15 times R1359,00 = R20 385,00 (if you earn less than R1359 you will get R20 385).The maximum lump sum 15 times R6 963,00 = R104 445,00 (if you earn more than R6963,00 you will get R104 445,00).If the degree of permanent disablement is 31% or more, you will not get a lump sum, you will get a monthly pension instead.The pension for total permanent disablement (degree of disablement 100%) is equal to 75% of your monthly earnings.If the degree of disablement is less than 100%, the pension is proportionately less.If the employee's earnings are R1 359,00 per month or less, the pension is calculated on R1 359,00.The minimum pension in respect of 100% permanent disablement is therefore R1 019,25 per month.Where an employee dies, the surviving spouse is entitled to* a lump sum equal to two times the monthly pension to which the employee would have been entitled to if 100% disabled* a pension equivalent to 40% of the pension to which the employee would have been entitled, if 100% disabled.Where the employee dies, each child under 18 years of age is entitled to a monthly pension equal to 20% of the pension which would have been payable to the employee for 100% disablement, up to a maximum of three children.The maximum pension payable to the spouse and children together is therefore R9 321,00 per month.All reasonable medical and transport costs arising from the accident are also paid for by the Compensation Fund.You can apply for compensation from the Compensation Fund at any of these labour centres.How does this compensation affect a Social Security grant?Home > Publications > Public Information > T > Government Financial Assistance &gt Road Accident Fund (formerly Multilateral Motor Vehicle Accidents Fund)Road Accident Fund (formerly Multilateral Motor Vehicle Accidents Fund)The Road Accident Fund (RAF) was set up to pay compensation in respect of people injured or killed in road accidents through the negligent driving of a motor vehicle in South Africa.The system was changed so that instead of compulsory insurance, there is now a fund, which gets its money from a levy on the sale of fuel.People can make a claim for compensation against the RAF if they are injured in a motor vehicle accident as a result of negligent driving.You must make your application to the RAF within 2 years of the date of the accident in which you sustained your injuries.You can make the claim yourself by completing Form 1 and submitting all the necessary documents; or you can get an attorney to help with your claim.The exact amount ("quantum") paid out for a claim against the RAF depends on your medical expenses, your loss of income (past and future), your disablement, and your pain and suffering.Road Accident Fund: Cape Town Contact Details:Physical Address7th FloorNo.1 Thibault SquareLong StreetCAPE TOWNPostal AddressPrivate Bag X28Tel : 021 408 3300Fax : 021 419 7417 / 8740How will compensation from the RAF affect a Social Security grant?If, taking into account any compensation you get from the Road Accident Fund, your income is still below the means test set by SASSA, you may qualify for one of the Social Security grants.In other words, if your income (including the compensation from the RAF) is less than R1410 per month, you may qualify also for the disability grant.Home > Publications > Public Information > T &gt Testicular CancerHome > Publications > Public Information > U &gt Patients Rights CharterHome > Publications > Public Information > V &gt Frequently Asked Questions for TenantsHome > Publications > Public Information > V &gt Questions and Answers about Measles & Polio ImmunisationHome > Your Government > Provincial Gov