 the payment of all the liabilities of the Trust upon dissolution of the Trust.Short titleThis Act is called the KwaZulu-Natal Business Rehabilitation Trust Fund Act Repeal Bill, 2008.THE KWAZULU-NATAL DUBE TRADEPORTCORPORATION BILL, 2008To provide for the establishment of a company known as Dube TradePort Corporation Limited to manage and undertake identified projects; to provide for the holding of shares in the company; to determine the company's objectives; to provide for the funding of the company; to provide for the appointment of a chief executive officer and a board of directors; to provide for matters related to the governance and management of the company by a board of directors and a chief executive officer; to determine the company's powers, functions, financial and operational accountability and to regulate its functioning; to provide for the formulation of regulations; and to provide for incidental matters.CHAPTER 1DEFINITIONSIn this Act, unless the context otherwise indicates ‚ÄïBoard means the Board of Directors contemplated in Chapter 3 of this Act;Chief Executive Officer means the Chief Executive Officer of the Corporation, contemplated in section 21;Corporation means the Dube TradePort Corporation Ltd registration no. 2005/030980/07, a private company with limited liability duly incorporated, as envisaged in Section 20 of the Companies Act and established in Section 2 of this Act,Head of Department means the person appointed as head of the Department in terms of section 12 of the Public Service Act, 1994 ;indirect interest includes, but is not limited to, an interest held by any director's:-Business partner, associate or employer, other than the State;Spouse, partner in a customary marriage, or person with whom such director cohabits or lives as though they were married;iii. Child, relative, or siblingKwaZulu-Natal means the province of KwaZulu-Natal contemplated in Section 103 of the Constitution;MEC means the Member of the Executive Council of KwaZulu-Natal responsible for economic development in the Province or any other Member of the Executive Council who has been assigned by the Premier;KwaZulu-Natal die provinsie KwaZulu-Natal bedoel in artikel 103 van die Grondwet;Portfolio Committee means the Portfolio Committee of the Provincial Legislature responsible for economic development;Province means the KwaZulu-Natal Province contemplated in section 103 of the Constitution;Provincial Government means the Provincial Government of the Province as constituted in terms of the Constitution;Public Finance Management Act means the Public Finance Management Act, 1999 and any amendments thereto and regulations made thereunder;the Act includes the regulations made thereunder.The object of this Act is to make provision for ‚Äïverbandhoudende projekte die projekte en besighede wat voortspruit uit of verband hou met die Dube TradePort projek wat deur die provinsiale regering in werking gestel is, en as sodanig deur die LUR aangewys is deur middel van kennisgewing in die Koerant;construction and operation of the Dube TradePort Project as well as any otherrelated projects.to create an environment which promotes cooperative governance andfinancial accountability in terms of the Public Finance Management Act.furthering the provincial obligations in terms of fostering economicand to provide for the development needs of the population of the Province.bevordering van die provinsiale verpligtinge in die kweek van ekonomiese ontwikkeling in die provinsie, om langtermyn belegging aan te trek, om in- en uitvoere aan te moedig deur die medium van die Dube TradePort, en om voorsiening te maak vir die ontwikkelingsbehoeftes van die provinsie se bevolking.DUBE TRADE PORT CORPORATION LTDEstablishment of Dube TradePort Corporation LimitedThe responsible Member of the Executive Council must, with the concurrence of the Executive council ‚Äïcause to be established and register a company, as defined in the Companies Act, 1973 subject to the approval of the Registrar of Companies, to be known as the KwaZulu-Natal Dube TradePort Corporation Ltd; or such other name approved by the Executive Council;acquire and hold shares as the only shareholder on behalf of Provincial Government in such a corporation;cause such a corporation to be listed as a Schedule 3 Part D public entity in terms of the Public Finance Management Act, 1999 as a Provincial Government Business Enterprise.Objects of CorporationThe objects of the corporation are to ‚Äïundertake or invest in projects associated with the Dube Trade Port;enable increased private sector investment, through the utilization of legally recognized commercial enterprisesfoster economic development in the Province;attract long term investments to the Province,encourage exports and imports through the Dube Tradeport;promote economic growth and prosperity; andaddress the developmental needs of the population of the Province.Roles and functions of CorporationThe corporation must ‚Äïbe responsible for the strategic planning, establishment, design, construction, operation, management and control of the Dube TradePort Project and all associated projects;utilise its assets in accordance with its Master Plan, and within the framework of Provincial Government policy.The corporation may be assigned roles and responsibilities by the Provincial Government.The corporation must not, without the prior written approval of the Executivepurchase its own shares or grant loans or advances upon the security thereof;purchase the shares of any company; orlend or advance money on security of a mortgage of immovable property or of a notarial or other bond or a cession thereof.CHAPTER 3GOVERNANCE OF THE DUBE TRADEPORT CORPORATIONBoard of directors of CorporationThe Board of Directors is the accounting authority of the corporation in terms of Section 49 of the Public Finance Management Act.The corporation acts through a board of directors.The MEC must, by notice in the Gazette as well as in at least two newspapers circulating the Province, invite the nomination of persons for the board of the corporation to be made within 21 days of the date of publication.The invitation for nominations in terms of subsection must specify the -requirements for nomination; anddate by which nominations must be received by the MEC.The MEC must consider all nominations submitted in response to the notice.The MEC may, appoint a selection panel of no less than two departmental senior officials and two Dube TradePort Corporation senior officials to review all nominations and make recommendations on the nominees to the MEC.Composition, appointment and remuneration of Board of DirectorsThe MEC must ‚Äïafter considering the recommendations, if any, of the selection panelreferred to in section 6, appoint a total of not less than three and notmore than eight persons, as directors of the board.when making the appointments, secure a balance of interests byconsidering race and gender, from amongst persons representing thefollowing categories ‚Äïat least one senior official, with fiduciary accountability, from thedepartment as an ex-officio member to the Board of directors; withoversight function on behalf of Provincial government;at least two members, which have knowledge and expertise inpersons from any other category considered necessary to ensurethe furtherance of the objects of the corporation.The MEC must, by notice in the Gazette and at least two newspapers circulating in the Province, invite public comment on the short list of candidates to be made within twenty days of the date of publication.After the expiry of the period for public comment referred to in subsection and considering any submissions, the MEC must in accordance with subsection appoint the requisite number of directors to the board.The board of directors may, from time to time, identify such other persons to serve on the board in accordance with the memorandum and articles of association of the corporation and accordingly make recommendations to the MEC for such appointment.All appointments made by the MEC must be done after consultation with the executive council and the relevant portfolio committee.A director appointed to the board is paid such remuneration and allowances as may be determined by the MEC in consultation with the Member of executive council responsible finance.A director of the board who is a member of the public service must not be paid remuneration in addition to his or her salary, except for travelling and out-of-pocket expenses related to the business or activities of the corporation in accordance with the relevant travel and subsistence policy of the Department.Appointment of Chairperson and Deputy Chairperson of BoardThe MEC must appoint a chairperson and a deputy chairperson of the Board.Persons appointed in terms of subsection must not be publicly elected members of national, provincial or local spheres of government.In the event of the office of chairperson being vacant or the chairperson is absent, incapacitated or refuses or fails to act as chairperson of the Board, the deputy chairperson is empowered to exercise all of the powers, rights, functions and duties of the chairperson during the period of such vacancy, absence, incapacity, refusal or failure.In the event that ‚Äïthe offices of both chairperson and deputy chairperson are temporarily vacant as a result of the delay in filling the vacancy; orboth the chairperson and deputy chairperson are absent or incapacitated or refuse or fail to undertake their duties; then,the members then present must appoint another member to act as chairperson during the period of the temporary vacancy, absence, incapacity, refusal or failure.Term of office of directors of the boardA member is appointed to the Board for a term of office equivalent to a period of five years or such lesser term as the MEC may determine.Different terms of office may be determined for the appointment of different directorsA director may be eligible for reappointment upon the expiry of his or her term of office, but may not serve as a director of the board for more than two consecutive terms.A person who has been appointed to fill a vacancy on the board is regarded as having served the full term of five years for which he/ she was appointed.Disqualification and termination of appointment to membership of the BoardNo person may be appointed as a director of the Board, or if so appointed must immediately cease to be a member if he or she-is or becomes an unrehabilitated insolvent;is or has been declared by a competent court to be of unsound mind;A disqualification under this paragraph ends five years after the sentence has been completed;has been or is removed from public office on account of misconduct;has failed to recuse himself or herself as is required by section 12;has engaged in conduct which, in the opinion of the MEC, brings or could bring the Department, or the activities of the board or the corporation into disrepute or threatens the integrity of the Department, board or corporation; orfailed to carry out the duties and functions of the board to the best of his or her ability.The MEC may terminate the appointment of the director of the board, after giving effect to any administrative rights of the director ‚Äïon any of the grounds provided for in subsection ;on the recommendation of the board, for reasons which are fair and just, by a resolution adopted with a supporting vote of at least two-thirds of the directors of the board; orupon failure by the director to comply with the provisions of this Act.The MEC must, on request of the director of the board whose services have been terminated as provided for in subsection give written reasons for the termination of service.Any vacancy on the board must be filled for the unexpired portion of the term for which the vacating director was appointed in the same manner in which the vacating director was appointed.The MEC must, upon termination of appointments as contemplated in this section, advise the executive council and Portfolio Committee of the terminationResignation of director of the boardA director of the board may, at any time and not less than thirty days written notice, resign save that the MEC or his or her nominee may accept a shorter period of notice where he or she is satisfied that to do so would not be detrimental to the efficient functioning of the board.Status of members and recusal of membersAll directors of the Board must be non-executive directors;Every director of the Board must, upon assuming office and at the beginning of every financial year of the Corporation, make a general disclosure of his or her interest in any company or other business interest in the manner provided for in section 234 of the Companies Act.Subject to the provisions of subsection, where, in relation to a matter being investigated, considered or voted upon by the Board, a director who has any direct or indirect interest which precludes or could preclude that director from performing his or her functions in a fair, unbiased and proper manner or where potential prejudice and/or conflict of interest is likely to arise, and he or she must not participate in the investigation, consideration or vote, and must recuse himself or herself from the investigation, consideration or vote.If at any stage during the course of any proceedings before the Board it appears that a director who is present at that meeting has or may have an interest contemplated in subsection, such a director must forthwith disclose the nature of his or her interest and leave the meeting so as to enable the remaining directors to discuss the matter and determine whether such director must comply with subsection above.Any disclosure and determination contemplated in this paragraph must be recorded in the minutes of the meeting in question.If it subsequently emerges that a director has failed to disclose an interest contemplated in subsection, then relevant proceedings of the Board will be invalidated.Where a director of the board or family member or close associate experiences a change in financial or any other interest as contemplated in this section, or acquires an interest in the Dube Tradeport project, the director of the board must within ten days of the date of such changed interest, submit a written declaration of the change of financial or other interests to the MEC.Failure to declare financial or other interestsA director who fails to make a declaration envisaged in section 12 may, subject to subsection be disqualified from remaining on the Board.The head of department or the chief executive officer of the corporation on becoming aware that a director of the board has failed to comply with the provisions of section 12 must investigate the matter and refer the matter to the MEC for appropriate disciplinary action.Filling of vacanciesIn the event of a vacancy in the office of chairperson or in the ranks of the directors of the Board occurring for any reason, the MEC may, subject to the provisions of this Act, appoint a person or persons to fill such vacancy or vacancies for a period of office determined by the MEC when making such appointment.Temporary suspension of chairperson or memberThe MEC may suspend a Member of the Corporation whilst the MEC is investigating allegations which, if found to be correct or substantially correct, could result in the member's appointment being terminated in terms of section 10.Publication of appointmentsWhenever appointing the chairperson, deputy chairperson or a director of the Board, the MEC must cause a notice to be published in the Gazette as soon as is practical after the appointment notifying the name of the appointee, the office held, the date of effect and period of appointment.Meetings of board of directors of corporationThe Board must meet at least three times a year at such times and places as the board determines.The first meeting of the Corporation must be held at such time and place as the chairperson may determine.The chairperson, or in the absence of the chairperson, the deputy chairperson ‚Äïmay convene a special meeting of the board;must convene a special meeting within fourteen days of the receipt of a written request signed by at least four members of the board to convene such a meeting.The quorum for a meeting of the Board will be a simple majority of the total number of members appointed at that time.A decision of the majority of the members present at a meeting of the Board will be a decision of the Board, and in the event of an equality of votes the chairperson will have a casting vote in addition to a deliberative vote.The Board may, in its discretion, allow members of the public to attend any meeting of the Board.The procedure at meetings of the board of directors must be as determined by the memorandum and articles of association of the corporation.The chief executive officer of the corporation must attend and participate, but may not vote, in a meeting of the board.If a director of the board has, in relation to any matter to be considered at a meeting of the board, any interest which precludes that director from acting in a fair, unbiased and proper manner in respect of his or her membership of the board, the director may not ‚Äïvote or in any other manner participate in that meeting of the board; orbe present at the venue where the meeting is held.Delegations by the BoardThe Board by special resolution may delegate any of the powers, functions or duties conferred on it to any member of the Corporation's staff, and may similarly withdraw any such delegation.The Board will not be divested of any power nor relieved of any function or duty it may have delegated.Any delegation made in terms of this Act ‚Äïmay be made on and subject to any conditions determined by the Board;must be in writing;may be given together with the power to sub-delegate on and subject to any conditions so determined .Minutes of proceedingsThe Board and its committees must have minutes kept and prepared of their respective meetings, and must have copies of the minutes circulated to their respective directors.The minutes so prepared, when signed at a subsequent meeting of the Board by the relevant chairperson, will, in the absence of proof of error therein, be deemed to be a true and correct record of the proceedings and matters which they purport to minute, and will be sufficient evidence of those proceedings and matters at any proceedings before a court of law, tribunal or commission of inquiry.Functions of the boardThe MEC after consultation with the Board may ‚Äïset strategic guidelines for the pursuit of the Corporation's objectives;issue written policy directives to the Board; orwithdraw or amend any policy directives so issuedThe board with the chief executive officer is responsible-to ensure that relevant and appropriate policies are developed in consultation with the MEC for all operational issues at the corporation;for the determination of a code of conduct, applicable to all staff of the corporation and justiciable for the purpose of disciplinary proceedings;to ensure the effective, efficient and economical use of the corporation's funds and resources;to promote and maintain high standards of ethics;for the prevention of conflict of interest;for the protection of confidential information held by the board; andTermination of entire BoardThe responsible Member of the Executive Council may, subject to subsection, terminate the appointment of ‚Äïall the members of the Board; orthe majority of the members of the Board, which termination may render the Board inoperable.In the event that the responsible Member of the Executive Council exercises his or her powers in terms of subsection, he or she may, notwithstanding the procedure for the appointment of the members of the Board set out in this Chapter, appoint persons to serve as members of the Board on an interim basis: Provided that-the persons appointed in terms subsection may not remain on the Board for a period of more than 90 days from the date of their appointment; andthe responsible Member of the Executive Council, shall, subject to section 2, appoint the members of the Board within 90 days of the appointment contemplated in subsection .CHAPTER 4CHIEF EXECUTIVE OFFICER AND STAFF OF DUBE TRADEPORT CORPORATIONAppointment of Chief Executive Officer of the corporationThe Board in consultation with the MEC must appoint a fit and proper person as the chief executive officer of the corporation for a term of five years.The chief executive officer is eligible for reappointment for one additional term of five years.Notwithstanding the provisions of subsection, and in the interests of the Corporation, the Board in consultation with the MEC, may consider the eligibility of the CEO for a further appointment subsequent to the period referred to in subsection and, to such further period as may be determined by the Board in consultation with the MEC.The appointment of the chief executive officer is subject to the conclusion of a written performance agreement entered into between that person and the board of directors.The board of directors and the chief executive officer may, in writing and by agreement, amend the performance agreement.The Board may, after consultation with the MEC, terminate the chief executive officer's employment in accordance with applicable employment and labour law.The chief executive officer must to be paid the remuneration and allowances as may be determined by the MEC in consultation with the MEC responsible for finance.The MEC must also determine the conditions of service and benefits applicable to the Chief executive officer.The chief executive officer is an ex officio member of the board of directors without voting powers.Sections 12 and 13 apply to the chief executive officer with necessary changes, except that he or she must disclose his or her interests or any conflict of interest to the Board of directors.Suspension and Removal from Office of Chief executive officerThe chief executive officer vacates office ‚Äïin the case of resignation, when the resignation takes effect;when, in terms of the Companies Act, the person holding that office has become disqualified to serve as the Director of the corporation;Upon having been removed from office in terms of subsection .Subject to subsection the Board, after consultation with the MEC, may remove the Chief Executive Officer from office ‚ÄïFor misconduct;For failing to perform the duties connected with that office or to perform them diligently and efficiently;If, because of any physical or mental illness or disability, the holder of that office has become incapable of performing or efficiently performing the functions and duties connected with that office.The Chief Executive Officer may not be removed from office unless the MEC is satisfied that removal from office is justified in the circumstances.The MEC may appoint an impartial person to investigate the allegations against the Chief Executive Officer.The MEC may not decide the matter unless the MEC is satisfied that the appointed impartial person ‚Äïhad given the Chief Executive Officer sufficient opportunity to respond to those allegations or show cause why they do not justify removal from office, and to make representations and give whatever explanations may be regarded as necessary; and,has duly considered the investigation report as to the truth or accuracy, or otherwise, of those allegations and/or as to the question whether or not they are sufficient to justify removal from office.The Board in consultation with the MEC may suspend the Chief Executive Officer from office pending the outcome of the investigation.Acting Chief Executive OfficerThe Board in consultation with the MEC may appoint any employee of the Corporation who is not disqualified in terms of the Companies Act to be a director of the corporation, to act as Chief Executive Officer during any illness or absence of the Chief Executive Officer, or while that office is vacant or if the holder of that office has been suspended.Any person appointed to act as Chief Executive Officer will be competent to exercise and perform all the powers, functions and duties concerned and imposed upon the Chief Executive Officer in terms of this Act, and are subject to all the obligations of the Chief Executive Officer.Any act being performed or done or omitted by that person during that period of appointment will be regarded as having been performed, done, or omitted by the Chief Executive Officer.Delegations by Chief Executive OfficerThe Chief Executive Officer, with the Board's approval, may delegate any of the powers, functions or duties of that office to any employee of the Corporation, provided that that delegation will not prevent the Chief Executive Officer from exercising that power.Functions of Chief Executive officerThe chief executive officer is responsible for ‚Äïthe day to day management of the corporation, subject to the direction of the board;the compilation of a business and financial plan and reports in terms of the Public Finance Management Act, 1999, for approval by the board;the appointment of staff of the corporation;the control of, and maintenance of discipline over staff of the corporation.to ensure that full and proper books of accounts and all the necessary records in relation thereto are kept;to ensure that the boards annual budgets, corporate plans, annual reports and audited financial statements are prepared and submitted to the Department in accordance with the Public Finance management Act, 1999 ; andthe submission for approval by the MEC ‚Äïa business plan for the corporation, containing measurable objectives; anda statement of the corporation's projected income and expenditure, in respect of the following financial year.The chief executive officer is the accounting officer of the corporation, and is an ex-officio director of the board, without voting powers.Staff of the CorporationWith the approval of the Board, the Chief Executive Officer may appoint staff for the Corporation to perform the work necessary for, or arising from the performance of the Corporation's functions in terms of this Act.The remuneration, allowances and service benefits of the Corporation staff will be determined by the Board from time to time in consultation with the MEC and the MEC responsible for finance.Any member of staff must not, without the prior written permission of the Chief Executive Officer, perform any remunerative work outside of his or her employment with the Corporation.The Corporation must establish and follow employment practices, which are fair and equitable.Sections 12 and 13 apply to the staff of the corporation with necessary changes, except that each staff member must disclose his or her interests or any conflict of interest to the chief executive officer.A member of staff of the corporation must not use his or her position or privileges, or confidential information obtained as a member of staff of the corporation, for personal gain or to improperly benefit another person.A member of staff of the corporation who fails or refuses to comply with the provisions of this Act is subject to disciplinary measures in terms of applicable employment and labour law, and the Public Finance Management Act, 1999 .The board must keep a register of the disclosed interests of members of staff and must update that register from time to time.CHAPTER 5FINANCES, ACCOUNTABILITY AND SHAREHOLDINGFundingThe funding of the Corporation consists of ‚Äïmoney appropriated to it by the Legislature in terms of the Departmental budget vote;any other proceeds realised through projects associated with the Dube Tradeport and its related projects; andany other lawful source approved by the Public Finance Management Act, as amended.The board and the corporation must utilise its funds to cover costs in connection with the performance of its duties and functions and the exercise of its powers in terms of this Act.The chief executive officer must, with the concurrence of the board, the MEC and the MEC responsible for finance ‚Äïopen an account in the name of the corporation with an institution registered as a bank in terms of the Banks Act, 1990 ; anddeposit therein all money received in terms of subsection .The chief executive officer must ensure that the board does not enter into any financial commitment beyond its approved budget and its accumulated reserves.Financial year-endThe financial year-end of the Corporation commences on 1 April of a particular year and ends on 31 March of the next year.Compliance with Public Finance Management ActThe Corporation will be a provincial government business enterprise as contemplated by section 1 of the Public Finance Management Act.The Board, as accounting authority for the Corporation, must, without delay, notify the National Treasury in writing of the establishment of the Board and request that it be listed in schedule 3 to the Public Finance Management Act.The Corporation must comply with the provisions of the Public Finance Management Act and the Treasury Regulations issued thereunder from time to time.Unless or until the shareholding held by the responsible Member of the Executive Council by virtue of his or her office on behalf of the Provincial Government in the corporation in terms of section 33 is reduced, divested or transferred as contemplated in section 33 in accordance with a programme contained in the memorandum and articles of association of the corporation, rendering the corporation no longer under the ownership control of the Provincial Government as defined the Public Finance Management Act, 1999, the relevant provisions of the Public Finance Management Act, 1999, applicable to a provincial government business enterprise and a provincial public entity as defined in the Public Finance Management Act, 1999, are applicable to the corporation.The Corporation may not borrow money or issue a guarantee, indemnity or security, or enter into any other transaction that binds or may bind the Corporation, unless such borrowing, guarantee, indemnity, security or other transaction, is authorised by the Public Finance Management Act, as amended.Annual ReportsThe Corporation must, not later than 31 July of each year, submit a report to the MEC on the activities of the Corporation for the twelve month period ending on the preceding 31 March, which report must be tabled in the Provincial Legislature by the MEC not later than 31 August of each year.The annual report must ‚Äïfairly present the state of affairs of the Corporation, its business, its financial results, its performance against predetermined objectives and its financial position as at the end of the financial year concerned;include the report of auditors on those statements;include the Annual Financial Statement contemplated in section 31; andinclude such other information as the MEC may in writing require or prescribe.Audits and Annual financial statementsThe books of account and other financial records of the Corporation must be audited annually by the Auditor-General or by a firm of auditors approved of by the Auditor-General.When submitting the annual report contemplated in section 30, the Corporation must also submit the audited Annual Financial Statement in subsection, for the relevant financial year.The annual financial statement must comply with any applicable national and provincial legislative requirements for financial reporting and accounting practices, including the Public Finance Management Act.The chief executive officer must within five months of the end of the financial year submit to the MEC for approval and then to the provincial treasury an annual report on its activities during that financial year and audited financial statements, for tabling in the Legislature.Companies ActThe Corporation, its staff and its Directors must at all time act with the utmost good faith, and comply with the provisions of the Companies Act.Share Capital and ShareholdingThe share capital of the Corporation will consist of R1000-00 divided into one thousand ordinary shares of R1-00 each and the initial issued share capital of the Corporation will consist of one hundred shares.The KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Government is the sole shareholder of the Corporation.The MEC exercises the powers and duties of the KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Government as shareholder of the Corporation.The Corporation may not acquire, transfer, cede, sell or otherwise dispose of a major asset or an interest in any other entity or commercial enterprise without the prior approval of the MEC, who may determine the terms and conditions of that acquisition, transfer, cession, sale or disposition.The total number of shares issued and allocated in the corporation must, initially, both as to the number and value thereof be determined by the Executive Council.The MEC may in consultation with the Executive Council, and in furtherance of the objects of this Act from time to time ‚Äïincrease the share capital of the corporation if he deems it to be desirableand in the interests of the corporation;CHAPTER 6GENERAL AND MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONSGeneral offences and penaltiesAny person who contravenes any provision of this Act is guilty of an offence and is, on conviction, liable to a fine, or to imprisonment for a period not exceeding five years or to such penalty as may be determined by the Companies Act.RegulationsThe MEC may, after consultation with the Portfolio Committee, and by notice in the Gazette, make regulations on matters relating to ‚Äïinvitation for nominations for appointments to the Board;terms and conditions of appointment of members of the Board,powers, duties and functions of public servants seconded to the Corporation;the payment to the Corporation of fees and charges arising directly or indirectly from any of the services provided or recognitions granted by the Corporation;processes and methods to evaluate the performance of the Corporation;cooperation agreements with governmental departments or public entities;measures to facilitate public access to information on the Dube TradePortmeetings and the manner of operation of the Board;the relevant provisions of the Companies Act, 1973 ; andthe memorandum and articles of association of the corporationany other matter which is necessary to implement the provisions of thisAct.Winding upThe Corporation may not be wound up except in terms of an Act of the Provincial Legislature.Short Title and commencementThis Act is called the KwaZulu-Natal Dube TradePort Corporation Act, 2008.The Act will come into operation when it is signed by the Premier and published in the Gazette.TRADE AND INVESTMENT AGENCY BILL, 2008To provide for the establishment of an economic development agency to be known as Trade and Investment KwaZulu-Natal in order to attract foreign and domestic investment and to generate exports and export capacity in the Province; to determine the objects, powers, duties and functions of the Agency; to determine the manner in which the Agency is to be managed, governed, staffed and financed; to provide for the formulation of a Provincial Investment and Export Policy; and to provide for matters connected therewith.ARRANGEMENT OF SECTIONSSectionDefinitionsCHAPTER 2TRADE AND INVESTMENT KWAZULU-NATALEstablishment of Trade and Investment KwaZulu-NatalObjects of AgencyPowers, duties and functions of AgencyBOARD OF AGENCYComposition of BoardDisqualification from being appointed to BoardDeclaration of financial or other interests of members of BoardFailure 