 will be able to get around easily .the aim is to have easy access between the system and other ways of getting around , such as walking , cycling , metered taxis , and park-and-ride facilities .a non-motorised transport plan is being developed for each of the stations .what does this mean for people in private vehicles ?where special busways are envisaged , some road space will be lost to private motorists , and traffic signals will prioritise public transport vehicles .this will encourage people using private cars to switch to using the new system .the separation of public transport from general traffic can be beneficial to both public transport and cars .the bus-minibus taxi lane on the n2 has saved private cars over 20 minutes in travelling time .streets where private motorists will lose road space to the new system are parts of the r27 and in the centre of town at hertzog boulevard , heerengracht , parts of adderley street , hans strijdom avenue and parts of western boulevard .who will run the system ?the city of cape town will build the special busways and specify the levels of service , cost of the fares and the kinds of vehicles to be used .private sector companies will provide the actual operations and services .the operator will be paid on the basis of how many kilometres the vehicles travel and by meeting other performance standards .there will be a separate tender process for an independent company to collect the fares .there will also be an oversight agency established to monitor the quality of the service and to deal with complaints from the public .what does this mean for the current operators ?the city of cape town is talking to representatives of the bus and minibus industry in order to ensure that they play a central role in the new system .the objective is to achieve a high quality of service while improving profitability and working conditions in the industry .what does this mean for workers in the industry ?the new system is expected to create many jobs , not just in the construction phase but also in the operations .working for the new system will mean permanent jobs with all the benefits of formal employment , such as job security , regular hours of work , predictable income , leave , sick leave and maternity benefits .the new system will have many benefits for workers in the industry .where is the money for this project coming from ?the system is being financed through support from national government and the city of cape town .all three spheres of government , including the western cape provincial government , are committed to transforming public transport in cape town .much of the funding is being made available to meet the cape towns requirements for hosting the 2010 world cup .when will all this happen and how will it affect me ?all the phase 1a routes are planned to be operating by march 2010 , which will allow time to iron out the inevitable teething problems by the time the world cup begins in june .from the end of 2008 , construction work can be expected on the main parts of the route ‚Äï especially in the city centre and on the green point / sea point route and between the city and bayside mall , along blaauwberg road and up to the du noon area .careful planning is being done to minimise any traffic impacts during construction .how can i get more information ?erm has been appointed by the city to engage the communities that will be directly affected by phase 1a .in late 2008 they will be contacting representatives of these communities and holding public events to explain the proposals in more detail .if you are interested in being involved in these public processes , please contact linda slabber by phoning 021 702 9100 or by emailing linda.slabber @ erm.com .the irt is a way of ensuring that all modes of public transport work together and have priority over private transport .a major part of this is a bus rapid transit system ‚Äï a fast , modern road-based system .cape towns irt system will be based on examples of rapid transit systems that are working well in many parts of the world , including latin america , asia , north america and australia .it can work well here too , giving capetonians a regular , frequent , fast and reliable form of public transport .how will the irt work ?there will be two parts to the service :trunk routesfeeder routeson the trunk routes there will be separate , dedicated busways for special 18-metre articulated vehicles .there will be weatherproof , enclosed stations in the centre of the road on these routes , which will ensure that the vehicles can move quickly past other traffic and that people can wait in safety and comfort .the feeder services , with shorter 8m and 12m vehicles , will carry people to the trunk routes in normal traffic with stations along the side of the road .each vehicle will have several wide doors that open level with the station platform so that lots of people can get in and out quickly .the service will operate for 18 hours a day and vehicles will be frequent .the frequencies will range between a few minutes in peak hours and at least three times an hour when there is less demand .fares will be affordable and comparable with those charged by buses and minibuses at the moment .where will the system go ?the city of cape towns aim is to establish an irt network across the city within 10 to 12 years .the network will ensure that over 75 of the people are within 500 meters of a high-quality public transport system .this can only be achieved one step at a time .there are four phases for rolling out the irt .the first phase will be done in two steps , one to be completed before the world cup in 2010 and the other soon after the event .phase 1a : this phase will provide a link from the airport to the city centre and from the city centre to green point , sea point and hout bay , and around the city bowl suburbs .phase 1b : the proposed routes will extend the first phase to include special busways to century city andmontague gardens and busways from the airport to bellville and durbanville , strand and gordons bay , claremont and constantia , and table view via century city .phase 2 : this phase will link the densely populated south east of the city , which includes mitchells plain and khayelitsha , to destinations across the peninsula .phases 3 and 4 : the final phases will expand and link routes to the complete network , including areas such as delft , blue downs and stellenbosch .what exactly will phase 1a include ?the map has solid lines representing trunk routes and dotted lines showing feeder routes .there will be two trunk routes :example of a feeder service bus .cape town is getting an integrated rapid transit systemthis document outlines :what an integrated rapid transit system ishow the system will workwhere the system will gohow the system will affect commuters , existing operators and other road userswhen the project will be implementedthe solid red line shows the route from the v & a waterfront , through the centre of cape town , through paarden eiland to bayside centre and along blaauwberg road to du noon , doornbach and killarney gardens .feeder routes , marked by dotted lines , will run around the city bowl suburbs , from the end of sea point to camps bay and on to hout bay , and from camps bay over kloof nek to town .on the west coast , the feeder services will run around table view and parklands , to bloubergstrand and atlantis , including the atlantis industrial area and saxonsea , and to mamre .the feeder service will also run along racecourse road , through montague gardens to century city and richwood .how did the city decide upon phase 1a ?as a host city for the 2010 soccer world cup , the city of cape town has signed a contract with fifa to provide transport services between the airport , the city centre and the green point stadium area .phase 1a also focuses upon delivering quality public transport to the west coast which includes some of the communities with the most pressing mobility needs , such as mamre , atlantis , doornbach , du noon , and the joe slovo informal settlement , near milnerton .this west coast area also currently experiences some of the most severe traffic congestion .on 27 august 2008 the city of cape town gave the go-ahead for phase 1a , and approved the budget of r1.3 billion .city of cape town : approved level 1 water restrictionsnotice to all users of municipal potable water : approved level one restrictions shall apply from 1 november 2005 .notice is hereby given in terms of municipality of the city of cape town : water services by-law to limit or restrict the use of water published in the provincial gazette no 5994 on 28 march 2003 , that with effect from 1 november 2005 and until further notice , certain revised restrictions , subject to the exemptions provided for , shall apply within the boundaries of the city of cape town .these revised restrictions are required to encourage the continuation of the good water management habits and practices already achieved by all water users , as negotiated with the department of water affairs .the purpose of this notice is to inform all municipal potable water users of the new level 1 water restrictions to be imposed as of 1 november 2005 , which will supersede the previous level 2 water restrictions .any person who wishes to be exempted from any restriction should do so by contacting the relevant offices listed below .any person who contravenes the provisions of this final notice will be guilty of an offence and be liable to payment of a fine .contraventions should be reported to the 24 hour number 0860 10 30 54 .approved level one water restrictions whilst the use of sprinklers on any given day is permitted , no person shall without prior written authority from the council water a garden , sports field , park , or other grassed area using potable water , b