r in cape town is of a high standard .this is due to the fact that most of the water consumed in cape town is abstracted largely from unpolluted mountain catchments .our scientific services department is equipped with some of the most sophisticated water testing instrumentation in the water industry .this , plus a highly skilled and experienced group of scientists and technicians guarantees that the water which is supplied to the consumer is of acceptable quality .the city of cape town is committed to providing quality tap water to its consumers .every effort is made to meet the highest international standards for drinking water .our scientific services department performs numerous tests on water samples which are taken from water treatment plants , service reservoirs and from various points within the distribution system .these tests must meet the recommended guidelines which are laid down in the south african national standards for drinking water .most frequently asked questionshow frequently does water get tested ?quality of the water to consumers is monitored weekly throughout the year at various points at the treatment plants and within the distribution network in the cape metropolitan area .is cape town water recycled ?no , we do not drink recycled water but , we do recycle water for other uses such as industrial and irrigation purposes that do not require potable water .why is my water sometimes white when i open the tap ?this is a harmless phenomenon and it is caused by presence of air bubbles .the bubbles are as a result of high pressure in the distribution pipes that transport water to your home .allow the glass to stand for a while and air bubbles will escape .why does my water taste and / or smell funny ?a swimming pool smell is caused by chlorine which is added to your water to kill bacteria .an earthy smell is caused by a harmless substance called geosmin .geosmin is produced by small water plants called algae which may be present in rivers and dams at certain times of the year , e.g. summer .is chlorine present in my water and why is it added ?chlorine is a disinfectant and kills bacteria in water .chlorine has been used as a disinfectant as far back as the late nineteenth century .it has gained popularity throughout the world as an antibacterial agent .the presence of chlorine in piped waters has prevented and wiped out waterborne diseases such as typhoid , cholera and dysentery in many parts of the world .in south africa it is added to drinking water to ensure the prevention of bacterial re-growth in the holding water reservoirs and the network of pipes that transport water from treatment plants to your home .the levels of chlorines are such that they are maintained from supply point right up to your home tap .is it better to drink bottled water than tap water ?there is no reason why people should drink bottled water in cape town .some people may choose to drink bottled water due to health reasons or taste preference .with no presence of disinfectant , water can be contaminated and bacteria can accumulate during storage .this happens mostly after bottling and while water stands on the shop shelf .to provide a set of regulations governing the avoidance , minimisation , generation , collection , cleaning and disposal of waste ; and for matters related thereto .indexconflicts with other legislationapplication of this bylawcategorisation of wasteobligations of waste generatorshazardous wasteevent wastepriority wasteemergencies requiring the management of wasteestablishment of formal communities or businessesappointment of waste management officerintegrated waste management planexemptions from submitting a waste management planstorage and transportation of wastecollection of wasterecycling , reuse and recovery of wasteprohibition of unauthorised disposal of wastelittering and dumpinglicencesaccredited waste management service provider and registration of persons 